\begin{abstract}
Automating clinical documentation can significantly reduce physician burnout. However, in linguistically diverse regions like India, doctors often speak with patients in local languages but write their clinical notes in English. To automate this, models must handle cross-lingual summarization reliably. In this paper, we evaluate open-weights 7B-parameter models (Mistral and Qwen) on doctor-patient conversations across 10 Indic languages. We deliberately constrain our hardware to a single 32GB VRAM GPU to mirror realistic, privacy-compliant hospital IT infrastructure. We test four approaches: Zero-shot, Few-shot, Translate-then-Summarize (via IndicTrans2), and Fine-tuning. To measure performance, we introduce a three-tiered evaluation framework. We move past standard n-gram metrics (ROUGE, BERTScore) by deploying a strict LLM-as-a-Judge protocol to measure Hallucinations, Omissions, Safety, and Faithfulness. Our results show that while local 7B models are viable for Indic clinical NLP, standard programmatic evaluation scripts fundamentally fail to capture clinical semantics, falsely penalizing models for valid medical synonyms.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Writing clinical notes takes up a massive portion of a physician's day. While Large Language Models (LLMs) are now heavily researched for summarizing English medical dialogues, they fail to reflect the reality of global healthcare. 

In India, clinical encounters are almost always multilingual. A doctor might consult a patient in Telugu or Dogri, but hospital policy dictates the final Electronic Health Record (EHR) must be written in English. If we want to automate this workflow, we need cross-lingual summarization models.

However, bringing AI into a hospital introduces strict constraints. First, due to patient data privacy laws, hospitals often cannot send transcripts to cloud APIs like OpenAI. Models must run locally. Second, hospital IT budgets are limited; running massive 70B parameter models is usually out of the question. Therefore, we focus our research strictly on 7-billion parameter (7B) models that fit comfortably on a single, legacy enterprise GPU (NVIDIA V100, 32GB VRAM).

The hardest part of clinical NLP is proving the model is safe. If an LLM invents a medication (a hallucination) or forgets to note a severe symptom (an omission), the consequences are severe. Measuring these errors automatically across 10 different languages is difficult. Standard metrics like ROUGE rely on exact word matching, which breaks down when dealing with medical synonyms or translated terms.

In this work, we test Mistral-7B and Qwen-7B across four generation pipelines. To evaluate them, we propose a three-tier framework that layers traditional NLP metrics with a novel, clinically-aware ``LLM-as-a-Judge'' auditor. 

