\section{Methodology}

\subsection{Task and Hardware Setup}
Our goal is to take a raw transcript in a source Indic language and generate a structured English clinical summary. We use a dataset containing parallel doctor-patient scenarios spanning 10 languages (Assamese, Bangla, Dogri, English, Gujarati, Hindi, Kannada, Marathi, Tamil, and Telugu).

All experiments were strictly constrained to an NVIDIA V100 (32GB VRAM) to prove feasibility for standard local deployments. We selected two models for this environment:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Mistral-7B-Instruct (v0.2):} A highly efficient model known for strong English instruction following and reasoning.
    \item \textbf{Qwen-7B:} Selected for its extensive multilingual pre-training, making it a strong baseline for native Indic processing.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{The Four Pipelines}
We test how best to handle the language barrier using four distinct approaches:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Zero-Shot:} The model receives the Indic transcript and is simply prompted to generate an English summary.
    \item \textbf{Few-Shot:} We provide in-context examples (Indic dialogue $\rightarrow$ English summary) to guide the model's formatting.
    \item \textbf{Translate-then-Summarize (TTS):} We use \textbf{IndicTrans2}, the current state-of-the-art open-source translation model for Indian languages, to translate the transcript to English first. The 7B model then runs a standard English-to-English summarization.
    \item \textbf{Fine-Tuning:} We adapt the model weights directly to the task using parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) on paired data.
\end{enumerate}

\section{The Evaluation Framework}
Because healthcare requires zero margin for error, we designed a three-tiered evaluation system to catch every possible failure mode. 

\subsection{Tier 1: Standard Generation Metrics}
First, we measure general text quality using standard NLP metrics. We compute \textbf{ROUGE} (1, 2, and L) to measure structural overlap with human reference summaries, and \textbf{BERTScore} to measure underlying semantic similarity.

\subsection{Tier 2: Clinical Hallucinations \& Omissions}
A summary can score highly on BERTScore but still invent a fatal dosage error. To test exact extraction, we created a \textbf{Master English Ground Truth} by extracting all Symptoms, Diagnoses, Procedures, Habits, and Treatments from the original English source texts using GPT-5. 

We then evaluate the summaries against this ground truth. We ran this evaluation twice to compare methods:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Programmatic Lexical Matching:} A Python script using fuzzy string similarity (threshold $> 0.8$) to find matches.
    \item \textbf{LLM-as-a-Judge:} GPT-5 acting as a clinical auditor to semantically map extracted concepts.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Tier 3: Safety and Trustworthiness}
Finally, we evaluate the holistic safety of the generated text. Using GPT as an expert judge, we score each summary on four axes:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*]
    \item \textbf{Faithfulness:} Does the summary accurately reflect the patient's timeline?
    \item \textbf{Safety:} Are there dangerous medical contradictions?
    \item \textbf{Trustworthiness:} Is the tone objective and professional?
    \item \textbf{Explainability:} Is the reasoning easy for a clinician to follow?
\end{itemize}

