\subsection{The Failure of Programmatic Evaluation}
Our most significant finding occurred during the Tier 2 evaluation. When we initially scored the models using the programmatic Python script, the performance appeared artificially low. A manual audit revealed that strict lexical matching algorithms fundamentally fail to grasp clinical semantics. We categorized these failures into three types:

\begin{tcolorbox}[colback=lightgray!30, colframe=primary, title=\textbf{Figure 2: Lexical vs. Semantic Evaluation Flaws}, arc=2mm]
\small
\textbf{1. Semantic Synonyms}\\
\textit{Ground Truth:} "hoarseness", "difficulty swallowing" \\
\textit{Summary:} "voice changes", "swallowing difficulties"\\
\textcolor{alert}{\textbf{Python Script:}} 2 Omissions, 2 Hallucinations (Failed)\\
\textcolor{secondary}{\textbf{LLM Judge:}} Exact Match (Passed)\\[2mm]
\textbf{2. Part-of-Speech Shifts}\\
\textit{Ground Truth:} "hydration" (Noun) \\
\textit{Summary:} "stay hydrated" (Verb)\\
\textcolor{alert}{\textbf{Python Script:}} 1 Omission, 1 Hallucination (Failed)\\
\textcolor{secondary}{\textbf{LLM Judge:}} Exact Match (Passed)\\[2mm]
\textbf{3. Broad vs. Specific Abstraction}\\
\textit{Ground Truth:} "soft diet", "dal", "yogurt", "khichdi" \\
\textit{Summary:} "nutrition management"\\
\textcolor{alert}{\textbf{Python Script:}} 4 Omissions, 1 Hallucination (Failed)\\
\textcolor{secondary}{\textbf{LLM Judge:}} Valid Clinical Abstraction (Passed)
\end{tcolorbox}

As shown in Figure 2, a standard evaluator will aggressively punish a model for summarizing a list of Indian foods ("dal", "khichdi") into "nutrition management." However, from a physician's perspective, this is a highly accurate and desirable abstraction. 

By replacing the Python script with our LLM-as-a-Judge protocol, the F1-scores stabilized, revealing that models like Mistral and Qwen are far more capable of trustworthy clinical reasoning than standard NLP benchmarks suggest.

\section{Conclusion}
This study proves that it is feasible to build safe, cross-lingual clinical summarization systems for Indic languages using hardware that local hospitals can actually afford. However, doing so requires a paradigm shift in how we evaluate these models. As our three-tier framework shows, relying on traditional text-overlap metrics creates a false picture of clinical utility. By adopting clinically-aware, LLM-driven auditing, we can confidently deploy smaller open-weights models to reduce physician burnout in linguistically diverse regions.

